main event: Two star-like objects were observed approximately 200 miles east of Nashville, Tennessee on June 8, 1966.
interesting points: The objects were observed lower and west of the moon, at around the 1:30-2:00 o'clock position.
The objects changed direction, one at 2:9 degrees and the second at 2:4 degrees, and then made a first disappearance and reappearance about 1,200 feet at the 2:0 level.
One object was described as a star-like object, while the second object was possibly a reflection of the moon on the windshield of an aircraft.
The objects were observed for about 10 minutes, with one object heading southwest toward the horizon and the other making a turn towards the northeast.
The conclusion was that one object was likely a planet (astro) and the second was a clear reflection of the moon.
location: Approximately 200 miles east of Nashville, Tennessee
